from scipy import stats

cancer_0 = df[df['Cancer'] == 0]['BMI_mapped']
cancer_1 = df[df['Cancer'] == 1]['BMI_mapped']

t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(cancer_0, cancer_1)
print("T-statistic:", t_stat)
print("p-value:", p_value)

According to EDA-cancer/noncancer, since p-value between BMI and Cancer was lower than 0.05, we can know that there's a meaningful relevance between BMI and lung cancer. But, according to this EDA, since p-value is higher than 0.05, we can't ignore the null-hypothesis. So we can conclude that BMI and incidence of Lung cancer have a relevance and we can't say BMI and small/non small size cancer have a relevance

from lifelines import KaplanMeierFitter

filter = df[df['Cancer'] == 1]
time = filter['Survival period']
event = filter['Death']

# Kaplan-Meier survival curve
plt.figure(figsize = (10,8))
kmf = KaplanMeierFitter()
kmf.fit(time, event)
kmf.plot()
plt.title('Kaplan-Meier Survival Curve - Small Cell', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('Time(days)', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Survival Probability', fontsize = 15)
plt.show()
